items.title: Senecio linearifolius var. denticulatus
items.content_text: Lots of young plants coming up close to the Baw Baw Alpine Village. S. linearifolius var. latifolius also grows nearby and it is probably one month ahead of var. denticulatus re flowering time.

items.title: Thelymitra cyanea
items.content_text: Growing in boggy area with plants like Drosera arcturi. From Neville Walsh, they are "very prone to that inky tip damage, although they seem to flower OK from that. It's pretty much an obligate dweller of sphagnum peats."

items.title: Olearia phlogopappa subsp. continentalis
items.content_text: Shrubs to about 2.5m tall. At Mushroom Rocks.

items.title: Lepidoptera spp., Stylidium armeria subsp. armeria
Caladenia alpina
items.content_text: Despite considerable variation I think all 5 plants pictured are Caladenia alpina. Last 2 pics are of the same plant.

items.title: Montia fontana
items.content_text: Only subsp. fontana has been recorded at Mt Baw Baw but I can't confirm without seed.

items.title: Daviesia laxiflora
items.content_text: Small tree.

items.title: Leptostigma breviflorum
items.content_text: A ground-hugging, dense, soft mat spreading to 50cm+. ID by Neville Walsh. A long way out of range for this species.

items.title: Psychrophila introloba
items.content_text: Growing in a marshy area with Drosera arcturi. ID by Neville Walsh.

items.title: Ozothamnus cuneifolius
items.content_text: Single plant growing in a rock face near Walhalla. ID by Neville Walsh.

items.title: Lycopodium fastigiatum
items.content_text: Thousands of plants but only two seen in flower.

items.title: Schoenus calyptratus
items.content_text: Tiny plants spreading to form a mat in inundated areas.

items.title: Ozothamnus secundiflorus
items.content_text: Leaves with midrib on lower surface tomentose = O. secundiflorus. Glabrous midrib = O. thyrsoideus.

items.title: Correa lawrenceana var. latrobeana
items.content_text: All plants had finished flowering except this one which was mostly in bud.

items.title: Richea victoriana
items.content_text: 1st pic shows glabrous flowering stem. No gap between leaves and first flower is another feature compared to R. continentis which has 4cm+ gap between leaves and flowers and a pubescent flowering stem

items.title: Richea continentis
items.content_text: 3rd pic shows pubescent flowering stem. 4cm+ gap between leaves and first flower is another feature compared to R. victoriana which has no gap between leaves and flowers and a glabrous flowering stem.

items.title: Viola hederacea subsp. nov. (Baw Baws)
items.content_text: Key features are 1) Flowers barely exceed leaves and 2) Flowers nod down when open (pic 1, 2 & 3) or don't open much at all (pic 4 & 5). Only 2 of about 100 flowers were open on this 20 degree, sunny-showery day.

items.title: Epacris microphylla var. rhombifolia, Zygoptera spp.
Epacris microphylla var. rhombifolia, Zygoptera spp.
Grevillea australis
items.content_text: Only found in and around swampy areas.

items.title: Asterolasia trymalioides
items.content_text: Only found in and around swampy areas.

items.title: Viola eminens
items.content_text: Short stem and leaves not perfect for eminens. Other plants were a little taller. Apparently Baw Baw is renowned for unusual Viola.

items.title: Herpolirion novae-zelandiae
items.content_text: Despite the common name, this plant tightly hugs the ground. Plants spotted by Steve Best.
